column13: 9095. Anderson, F. J. April 22. Slide rules. - A long scale for a common logarithmic slide rule is broken up into parts of equal length, each representing numbers between consecutive integral powers of some chosen power of 10, these parts being placed as parallel scale s, one above the other, upon the two limbs or edges of the rule, the slider being similarly divided. In operating, addition or subtraction of numbers borne by the scales produces the number of the scale upon which the result will be found with the decimal point in the correct position, in a manner analogous to the use of the characteristics of logarithms. The graduations of the scales upon one limb are twice the size of those upon the other, whereby numbers may be squared and cubed, or the corresponding roots taken. Fig. 4 shows a rule with an upper limb A divided into parts representing numbers from 1 to #10, #10 to 10, and so on, a similar slide B, and a lower limb with double length graduations, i.e., with sections from 1 to <4>#10, <4>#10 to #10, and so on, these graduations thus representing, in position, the logarithms of the squares of the same numbers on the upper limb. Fig. 7 shows a glass cursor and frame, bearing the characteristic numbers A', B<1>, C' of the three scales, corresponding numbers appearing upon transverse index bars, Fig. 8, borne one at each end of the slide. In multiplying, the left or right index of the slide is placed against one factor on the upper limb, and the product found on the same limb exactly over the reading of the other factor on the slide. The characteristic number of the product scale is the sum of the two factor scales in the case of the left index, or the sum increased by unity in the case of the right index. Similar rules hold for other operations. Slides with trigonometrical and other scales may be used, and constants specially marked upon the limbs, colours being, preferably, used to distinguish unit from subdivision marks. The arrangement renders any system of subdividing the units possible.

PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To reduce mass of a carriage/actuator assembly for a head having a servo mechanism for positioning a track, in a magnetic tape drive. SOLUTION: A carriage 24 with a head 18 attached moves vertically along a guide rail 26, 28 by a voice coil motor installed under a plate 36. Since the carriage 24 partially bites inside the voice coil motor, the center of gravity of the carriage 24 is at a position close to the center of a force applied by the voice coil motor. Accordingly, the counter weight that is required for preventing the carriage 24 from swinging by this force by coinciding both positions can be made extremely small, thereby a servo system with a superior responsiveness is obtained.

column13: 20,570. Anderson, J. W. Oct. 12, 1904, [date applied for under Patents Act, 1901). Kinematographs. - Relates to a camera for taking a number of successive photographs on a plate, film, or the like, in more or less rapid succession, the camera being also adapted to be used as an ordinary one for taking ordinary photographs. When the camera is used for taking multiple photographs, the plate is moved intermittently across the light aperture, and it may be dropped a step at each end of its motion to enable a number of rows of photographs to be taken on one plate. The back B, which may be applied to any suitable camera, contains a removable diaphragm 2, the light aperture 3 in which can be adjusted, according to the number of rows of photographs it is desired to produce, by a vertically adjustable hinged flap 4, Fig. 3, engaged by a catch 7 at one end and carried by an adjustable rod 6 at the other end. The plate holder 13 and its sheath 14 are provided with vertical guides 11 carried by a base 8 mounted on rollers 9. In producing photographs in rapid succession, the plate is moved horizontally intermittently by a pin on a chain 31 engaging a slotted part 33 hinged to the carrier. The chain 31 passes over sprocket-wheels operated by pawl and ratchet-wheel gearing 26 connected, as shown, to a crank spindle 19. The plate holder 13 has a pin 16 engaging a slot in the cover 14 and adapted to engage a hook 18 to hold the two parts together when removed from the camera. Before exposure, the holder and its cover are raised until a pin 35 engages a catch 36, and the pin 16 is brought above the upper of a series of guide shelves 38 arranged as shown. When the plate is moved into position to take the first photograph, the pin 35 is released, and the cover 14 drops. The distance the plate drops at the end of a row of photographs is determined by the guide shelves 38, which can be adjusted by their projecting ends 39, Fig. 4, so as to allow the plates to fall through a distance equal to the space between any number of shelves at once. When the camera makes its last reciprocation, it trips an indicator 40. To prevent exposure during the motion of the plate, there is used a shutter composed of two semicircular parts 41, 42 mounted on a shaft 43 operated in unison with the photographic plate by the gearing shown. The size of the shutter aperture 45 is adjusted by moving one part 42 with respect to the other part 41, the two parts being held together by locking- devices 44. When the camera is used as a multipleview camera with time exposures, the shutter is folded up, and the operating-gearing is dispensed with, the plate carrier being moved horizontally by a bar graduated to enable the carrier to be moved the proper distance ; when it is used as an ordinary plate camera, the diaphragm 2 may be removed also, and the plate-holder guides are arranged horizontally and the plate &c. holder is moved into and out of its cover by a rod engaging the pin 16.

column12: Process and related apparatus for repairing aquatic propeller scars and blowouts
column13: A process and apparatus for planting aquatic plants underwater on the bottom of estuaries in propeller scars and blowouts and for encouraging plant growth in these propeller scars and blowouts. Aquatic plant shoots are transplanted by positioning shoots, plants or seeds in a sediment tube or sediment bag which is in turn placed in a propeller scar or blowout. When the sediment tube or sediment bag is placed in the propeller scar or blowout aquatic plant growth is facilitated. The sediment tubes and sediment bags may be preformed or they may be formed just prior to their placement in the estuary. A watercraft may be used to position the sediment tubes and sediment bags with and without sea grass shoots, plants or seeds, in propeller scar propeller scar. With the process and apparatus of this invention, sea grass plants can be replanted on the bottom of an estuary and new plant growth encouraged in propeller scars and blowouts.. Further in accordance with another embodiment of this invention a tube or other obstruction without plant shoots, plants or seeds is placed in a propeller scar in order to impede water flow through the propeller scar. When water flow through the propeller scar is impeded natural plant growth is encouraged. The material from which the sediment tube or bag is formed from degrades. The degration of the sediment tube or bag can be correlated to the growing cycle of seagrass plants, shoots or seeds as may be contained in the sediment tube or bag.

column13: 6764. Anderson, J. C. April 10. Motor road vehicles. - Relates to motor carriages, and comprises a construction of such a carriage in sections articulated together. each section being supported on two wheels and having seats for two or three persons. Fig. 1 shows in elevation, and Fig. 2 in plan, a vehicle composed of two sections ; modifications with three sections are also shown in the Specification. The frames, built of tubes A, B, C, E, are articulated together at the upper and lower ends of centrally-situated vertical tubes F, F<1>. The tube F carries brackets G, through which passes a long bolt or pivot having ball bearings in the tube F<1>. The wheel forks P, in the example shown, are horizontal, and are pivoted on journals N projecting from the frames, the weight of the vehicle being supported on the wheel axles through the medium of plunger rods S and springs located in tubular receptacles V forming part of the frame. The springs are cylindrical rubber bodies having longitudinal cells inflated by means of liquid air or other expansible substance. The independence of the wheels allows the vehicle to accommodate itself readily to uneven roads. Any suitable motive power may be employed, such power being applied through the medium of sprocket chains C' driven by chainwheels B<1> at the ends of a divided balance shaft. The balance gear employed is shown in Fig. 3. The two portions 6, 6 of the divided shaft are geared together by a chain 12 having the alternate links pivoted together at right-angles. This chain passes over sprocket-wheels on the two parts of the shaft and on a transverse shaft 8 mounted in the driving-box 1. In addition to the articulation at G, the several sections of the vehicle are connected together by links 22, by means of which steering is effected. Multiprocessor system with cache controlled scatter-gather operations
column13: Dynamic cache architecture for a multi-processor array. The system includes a plurality of processors, with at least one of the processors configured as a parent processor, and at least one of the processors configured as a child processor. A data cache is coupled to the parent processor, and a dual port memory is respectively associated with each child processor part and parcel of a unified memory architecture. The parent processor may then dynamically distribute sub-cache components to dual-port memories based upon a scatter-gather work unit decomposition pattern. A parent cache controller reads, in response to a memory request from a child processor and an address translation pattern from the parent processor, a set of data from non-contiguous addresses of the data cache according to the address translation pattern, and writes the set of data to contiguous addresses of the dual port memory associated with the requesting child processor.

An on-hook and off-hook detector is provided for each of the telephone extensions a s well as a detector for detecting the presence of an incoming call on the externa l channel. A switching circuit is then responsive to an off-hook status of a first extension together with a coded audio signal generated by the buttons at the fir st extension to either (1) selectively and exclusively connect the first extension to a selected second extension determined by the coded audio signal to the internal channel and to generate a ring signal to the second extension, or (2) connect th e first extension to the external channel. The switching circuit is also responsive to a coded audio signal to transfer an incoming call from the first extension to a selected second extension. Other features, including area code lockout features and placing an external call on hold, are also disclosed.

column13: Forward link transmission power to a user terminal in a wireless communications system having a plurality of beams is controlled by determining a baseline power level, P baseline , from a received active pilot channel signal-to-noise ratio (SNR); determining a power margin, P margin , from an identified interference susceptibility; determining a power level correction, P correction , based on an identified quality of service metric (QSM); determining a fade correction factor, P fade , based on a detected fade environment; and setting P transmit based on P baseline , P margin , P correction and P fade . For example, P transmit may be set to a power level that is substantially equal to the sum of P baseline , P margin , P correction and P fade . The determination of each of P baseline , P margin , P correction and P fade may be performed in independently running control loops or processes.

column13: A moisture tester for measuring the total moisture content of high moisture feed products such as corn, silage and cut hay including a probe or sensor having spaced apart electrodes in contact with the product. A VCO is coupled to the electrodes for producing a variable frequency signal proportional to the resistance across the electrodes. A time base signal generator produces a relatively slow fixed frequency time base signal. A gate timer produces latch and reset signals from the time base signal for use in a BCD counter incorporating latch, multiplex and BCD counter portions. The resulting output from the BCD counter drives a display device to provide the user with a relative indication of the amount of moisture over a range of moistures in the feed product. Also disclosed are several types of probes. One flat plate type includes coaxially-mounted annular electrodes for measuring the moisture of newly cut hay. Another sensor measures the moisture of loose feed products using a conical bucket having electrodes mounted on its interior walls.
